<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-860-443  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 860 443.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  August 1989 v62 n8 p61(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Losing the edge in production equipment. (semiconductor productionequipment)(includes related article on new firms pushinginnovative technologies for market niches)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cole, Bernard C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US semiconductor equipment manufacturers are contending withserious long-term problems which can be corrected only by basicstructural changes in the way they do business and concomitantchanges in the electronics industry, otherwise they will bedominated by the Japanese.andP;  While many established vendors areleaving the industry, others are changing their development andmarketing strategies and many start-ups are offering uniquetechnologies for niche markets, according to one observer.andP;  Japanwill probably exceed the US's share of the wafer-fabricationequipment market for the first time at the end of 1989.andP;  Thereasons why the US semiconductor equipment industry is not doingwell include poor balance sheets, faulty market forecasting, poorproduct planning and marketing, inattention to customers' needs,arrogance, and a relatively closed Japanese market.andP;  Largesemiconductor equipment manufacturers are reducing investments andfocusing on a few product areas, getting out of the industryaltogether, or investing in new technology, expanding productlines and competing with Japanese companies in Japan.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Semiconductor production equipmentIndustry AnalysisForeign CompetitionJapanese CompetitionSemiconductor industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   The top 10 semiconductor production equipment makers in 1988 and1979. (table)Market entries and exits among US and Japanese suppliers. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>